                        <h4 class="modal-title" id="project-4-label">AI &amp; ML
                          Driven Autonomous Navigation</h4>
                      </div>
                      <div class="modal-body">
                        <h3>Project Description</h3>
                        <div class="row">
                          <div class="col-md-6">
                            <p>A few years ago I was part of Queen's Mostly
                              Autonomous Sailboat Team and my role was to
                              program a boat to sail autonomously. At that time
                              I wanted to implement artificial intelligence
                              controller for the navigation, however, due to
                              hardware constraints such a controller wasn't
                              used. Things has changed, hardware-wise, since
                              last time I worked on such problem and now with
                              the advances in artificial intelligence it is the
                              right time to work on the same problem again. This
                              project focuses on using data driven approach to
                              programming robots to navigate environments and
                              follow a prescribed trajectory. </p>
                            <p>The trajectory tracking problem is a well known
                              problem in control theory in which the aim is to
                              find an input to the dynamical system that would
                              result in a path close the predefined one. There
                              are three ways in which one can implement a
                              trajectory tracking method: using classical
                              control theory tools, using a deep neural network
                              controller, or reinforcement learning. Here we
                              will only focus on the first approach, however,
                              the mathematical model is not known to us
                              beforehand and for that system identification
                              using regression is used to construct a
                              mathematical model heuristically. </p>
                            <p>The first step in modelling the robot is by
                              collecting the system's response to known input
                              signals, i.e. give the robot a set of predefined
                              commands and observe the behaviour. After data is
                              collected, the data is used to solve a regression
                              problem which yields an expression for the
                              dynamical equation. Then an optimal control
                              problem is solved to obtain a controller. As a
                              testing problem for this automated framework, a
                              trajectory tracking problem for a Dubins car type
                              vehicle, that moves forward the control is the
                              steering angle. The result can be seen in the
                              figure on the right. </p>
                            <p>Another way of tackling navigation problem is
                              implementing an evolutionary robotic paradigm.
                              Here the vehicle is Reed-Shepp type car where the
                              speed and steering are the controls. The vehicle
                              is equipped with five forward facing proximity
                              sensors whose readings are fed, along with the
                              vehicle's position, as inputs to the control
                              neural network. The control here is implemented
                              using feed-forward multilayer perceptron. Other
                              network architectures can be used and the it is on
                              the todo list to use reservoir computers for
                              control. Most evolutionary process are implemented
                              using genetic algorithms, here particle swarm
                              optimisation is used to evolve the weights of the
                              control neural network. </p>
                            <p> Here, the particle swarm optimisation algorithm
                              was interpreted as a Hamiltonian system. The
                              advantage of using Hamiltonian dynamics with PSO
                              is that it allows us to construct geometric
                              integrators for the problem, which will circumvent
                              a number of problems encountered by a naïve
                              implantation the algorithm. </p>
                            <p>Instead of describing it as a system of equation
                              for the swarm in terms of position, \(x_i\) and
                              velocity \(v_i\) as it is usually done, we
                              describe it in terms of position \(q_i\) and
                              conjugate momentum \(p_i\). The Hamiltonian here
                              is a function \(H: \mathrm{T^{\ast}Q} \to
                              \mathbb{R}\) given by </p>
                            $$ \begin{aligned} H(p, q) &amp;= T + V_s + V_m \\
                            &amp;= \frac{1}{2} \| p_i \|^2 + V_s(q_i) + V_m
                            (q_i), \end{aligned} $$ where \(V_s : \mathrm{Q} \to
                            \mathbb{R}\) is the social potential and \(V_m:
                            \mathrm{Q} \to \mathbb{R}\) is the memory potential.
                            By potential, we don't mean ''possibility of
                            achieving", but rather as a potential energy. With
                            that, the Hamilton's equation of motion is $$
                            \begin{cases} \dot{q_i} = \frac{\partial H}{\partial
                            p_i},\\ \dot{p_i} = -\frac{\partial H}{\partial q_i}
                            \end{cases} $$ <a href="https://github.com/NaderTG/Hamiltonian_Particle_Swarm_Optimisation">My
                              C++ implementation can be found here</a> </div>
